\begin{abstract}
Emulating long-term, stable N-body gravitational dynamics is challenging for standard neural networks, which often violate fundamental physical conservation laws, leading to unphysical behavior. We address this by developing a neural ordinary differential equation framework that learns the underlying conservative vector field of the system. Our approach parameterizes the Hamiltonian using a permutation-invariant graph neural network and embeds a differentiable leapfrog integrator directly into the training loop, which constrains the learned dynamics to be symplectic. The model is trained on trajectory snapshots from simulations of 50-particle virialized Plummer spheres, explicitly incorporating a gravitational softening length as a physical prior and employing a curriculum learning strategy to manage the system's multi-scale nature. Our results show that the model reconstructs system trajectories and generalizes in a zero-shot manner to systems with different particle counts. Critically, the learned emulator demonstrates long-term stability by preserving the geometric structure of the dynamics: it exhibits bounded energy error without secular drift, respects time-reversibility, and conserves phase-space volume, demonstrating that enforcing physical constraints is crucial for building robust emulators of chaotic systems.
\end{abstract}
\end{document}

